      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh okay that makes sense. so if i'm trying to get a really good crust on a loaf of sourdough, what should i be looking for in terms of moisture or temp to get that reaction going? like how do i control it so it doesnt just burn?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To get that perfect crust, you need to manage moisture carefully; a hot, dry oven environment helps trigger the Maillard reaction on the surface while keeping the interior soft. Aim for a temperature between 200°C and 230°C (400°F–450°F) for the first 10–15 minutes to brown the crust without burning it. You can control the timing by using steam in the early stages, which delays the reaction until the crust forms, then venting the steam to allow browning to finish. If the bread looks too dark too soon, simply lower the oven temperature slightly or reduce the baking time.",
