      "content": "Yes, acidity plays a crucial role because the Maillard reaction speeds up significantly in an acidic environment, which is why sourdough often browns faster than neutral doughs. To control this, you can adjust the fermentation time to increase natural acidity from wild yeast, or add a small amount of acid like lemon juice or buttermilk if you need to speed up the browning. However, be cautious not to over-acidify, as it can make the dough too sour or inhibit yeast activity. If the crust is browning too quickly, you might need to reduce the oven heat slightly to balance the chemical reaction with the thermal energy.",
